    <h1>Chang&#xAD;ing face of the Olympics</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201220/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-20"><time>2020-12-20</time></a>
        - <span>SPORT</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Next year ’s post­poned Games will see a host of new sports – rep­re­sent­ing the big­gest change in the mod­ern Olympic pro­gramme. As ad­di­tions are in­tro­duced for the Tokyo and Paris edi­tions, we look at when key sports made their Olympic de­buts.</p>
    <p>At­lanta 1996 Ber­lin 1936</p>
    <p>St Louis 1904 • Div­ing</p>
    <p>• Box­ing</p>
    <p>Paris 1900</p>
    <p>Foot­ball joins the pro­gramme and re­mains in ev­ery edi­tion ex­cept in 1932.</p>
    <p>Golf makes the first of two straight Olympic ap­pear­ances be­fore re­turn­ing only in 2016.</p>
    <p>Rugby ’s 15-a-side ver­sion joins the Games. In 2016, rugby sevens takes its bow.</p>
    <p>• Artis­tic gym­nas­tics, ath­let­ics, cy­cling, fenc­ing, shoot­ing, swim­ming, ten­nis, weightlift­ing and wrestling were in the first mod­ern Games. Bad weather forced the can­cel­la­tion of sail­ing races but the sport re­mains a main­stay.</p>

